This would have also prevented having a separate .tsx extension as the editor could simply determine if <> is a component and switch the syntax it writes to TS files on the fly.

This is basically just a compiler macro in reverse. Instead of writing code that uses macros in your build tool (leading to nonstandard JS), you edit a macro in your editor and write standard JS to files.

That way there's no build tooling support required, JSX return types actually work property in TS, and any editor can edit createElement while editors supporting some sort of shared plugin or language service can enable JSX editing mode automatically when parsing createElement.

I think the mistake React made with JSX (especially with TS type safety) was having it be a nonstandard syntax that compiles to JS. It should have been a way of writing standard createElement function calls in JS/TS files but showing them as JSX tags in the editor instead.
